Russia and Turkey: “Incompatible” Alliances?
It was a gesture that ended in a crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce a formal end to the eight-month-long verbal war and economic sanctions.
But while Vladimir Putin welcomed the Turkish counterpart in the luxury hall of the St. Petersburg Palace, I had the impression that Ankara wanted this reconciliation more.
It was a handshake, yes.
But Putin did not laugh and hardly radiate heat from it, even by his measured standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken about his "dear friend" to Mr Putin - five times, according to one report.
I didn't count it.
He also promised that relations with Russia will not only return to their pre-crisis level, but they will be even better.
The next day, a local newspaper reported that Erdogan was acting as if nothing bad ever happened.
I think his enthusiasm revealed the exact opposite.
But the persistent cold that radiated from Putin has shown that the Russian leader has not forgotten anything.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: the shooting down of a Russian warplane by Turkey on the Syrian border.
Moscow’s reaction was furious at the time.
Putin was lashing out and accusing Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The embarrassment was all the greater because it came from a supposed friend.
Rebuilding real trust will be difficult, perhaps even impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
State-controlled media for months led a massive nationwide campaign against Ankara.
All of a sudden, it looked like the Turks could do anything.
More serious were accusations from top officials that Erdogan’s own family benefited from the illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He strongly denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message came that it is time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Putin got the apology he asked for from President Erdogan.
Russia could have declared a victory as well.
For Ankara, the benefits of the truce are clear.
In the first place, Erdogan was almost powerless during the failed coup last month and therefore needs all his friends.
Repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have also visibly shaken him.
There is also an economic motive.
Russia’s sanctions have had a severe impact – notably the cancellation of charter flights that transport several million Russian tourists to Turkey’s coast every year.
This number decreased by almost 90%.
As far as Russia is concerned, tour operators and charter companies are sure to take a rest when the flights are resumed.
They make money on the Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television promised cheaper fruits and vegetables when the import of agricultural commodities from Turkey will be allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as reported in the Vedemosti newspaper.
The visit, however, had another political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry at the West for what it considers a weak response to the coup attempt.
In addition, the long-standing hostility of lengthy talks about joining the EU and Putin’s entry – who yearns to be able to take advantage of the cooling and break Turkey’s ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly earned bonus points when Ankara asked him for the help of the elected authorities after the coup attempt.
You must understand that for Moscow, which has a deep-seated fear of regime change, this is the case.
So the summit in this pompous, seaside palace allowed Russia and Turkey to show what one analyst described to me as “an alliance of the incompatible”: how the forces of the two countries feel to be rejected and exploited by the West.
However, despite the fact that they have publicly shown mutual reconciliation, there are fundamental differences between the two countries.
The first is Syria, where Moscow recently took on the role of peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey stand on opposite sides.
