The so-called tourist SIM is also intended to help detect people who exceed the allowed length of stay.
Within six months, special SIMs for foreigners should also be available for retailers, along with a SIM exclusively for Thais.
The difference will be the tracking function, which will be permanently switched on for cards intended for people without a Thai passport.
It won't be possible to turn it off.
"This feature is not for Thais because we can always easily track them," Tantasith added.
It should be noted that in Thailand prepaid cards are not anonymous as in the Czech Republic.
The seller requires proof of identity.
On the other hand, for several years, one of the operators distributed a free start-up SIM to tourists at the airports.
They were completely anonymous.
The introduction of the same measure as Thailand is also being considered by ten telecommunications regulators from other Asian countries including, for example, Malaysia and Singapore.
They also currently have a mandatory SIM registration, but legal use of the tracking system is not possible.
However, the proposed measure does not imply an obligation for foreigners to acquire a local operator when entering the country of SIM.
They can of course use roaming services with their own home SIM, in which case the Thai authorities will be short on them.
The operators of the country in question know only the relevant network information after crossing the border, i.e. after logging in to their network.
They know the phone number, but not the owner’s information.
However, the difference in roaming prices compared to the rates of local operators is so vast that most tourists will begin to look for local SIMs during their stay in Thailand.
The authorities’ efforts to monitor the movement of foreigners have received immediate criticism from foreigners living in Thailand.
Tantasith calms the situation and, in the context of privacy protection, the planned system compares it to the obligation to provide a residence address in immigration documents.
In addition, the police will need a court order if there is a need to monitor a particular person.
Any abuse of the system will be subject to an unspecified penalty.
"If the service provider monitors the location of the SIM without a court order, he will be charged with a criminal offence," Tantasith added.
The system should also maximize the use of prepaid cards.
While a specific number will not be recycled until after the 90-day period after which the SIM did not sign in to the network, a new one could be recycled after 15 days if it leaves Thailand.
Luxury apartment in a new building in Vinohrady has a swimming pool and a jacuzzi on the terrace.
Why did you choose an apartment in a new building?
We were looking for a carefree apartment where most of the care of the property is taken by the manager.
The condition was enough parking spaces and an elevator in the house, which basically disqualified the older building.
Not to mention problematic acoustics in old houses, problems with swinging the floor, high energy efficiency and the like.
The condition was also large terraces, which the old building is not able to offer.
Other interesting visits can be found in the magazine Modern<0xC3><0xAD> apart.
The whole interior was designed for you by architect Lenka Langerov<0xC3><0xA1> and her colleague Kamila Pol<0xC3><0xA1>kov<0xC3><0xA1> from the Artiga studio.
Why did you just call them?
Would you recommend working with an expert to everyone?
We would recommend cooperation with the architect to anyone, if he proposes an apartment from the beginning, it is a very complex technical process.
The second level is the interior design itself: designers have a significantly better idea of the range of possible materials, and based on the client's wishes they are able to align the interior appropriately.
We collaborated with the architect Lenka Langerova on our mountain apartment, then based on the personal recommendation of another client, and since everything worked well, there was a clear choice for us during the reconstruction of our new apartment in Vinohrady.
What were your practical and aesthetic requirements?
We wanted a generous social-living space with adequate facilities for a four-member family, conceived as a modern, but not a cool interior.
The priority was to achieve the connection of the apartment with the terraces and to implement intelligent control of the house.
Of course, the quality of the work had to be monitored.
Have you left everything to the experts, or have you yourself interfered with the final form of the interior?
We have approved all designs, including technical drawings and samples of materials, but the design has always come from the architects.
At the beginning, we set out what we expect from the design, and showed some interior elements that we would like to incorporate into the design, such as carpets or paintings.
I think that it was our collection of mostly Czech authors including works by Karl Malich, Karl Vysushil, V<0xC3><0xA1>clav <0xC5><0xA0>p<0xC3><0xA1>la or Otto Gutfreund that helped the architect to orient herself in our taste.
The combination of black, white and walnut wood was also the architect’s idea as well as the individual pieces of furniture, walls, floor, lighting, carpets, textiles, art, etc. We then verified together by visualization.
Were there any complications in the realization that made you have to give up your original ideas or, conversely, start a new one?
Perhaps only in the initial phase of the project, when we came to the building at the moment when it was for the first time possible to climb to the height of our floors, and found that the views we had planned, in fact, shaded the surrounding buildings.
Then we literally changed the disposition overnight from the base.
On the kitchen line and on the lining of the fireplace wall granite was used.
The interior is dominated by wooden surfaces supplemented by leather, for example on the upholstery of the Norma dining and bar chairs from Arper.
How would you characterize the interior?
Are you going to make a change or is there something you wish you had differently today?
I believe that this is a modern airy interior, which above all fulfills its purpose.
We are not planning any changes, most of the adjustments after the move took place in the shade and the habitation of the terraces.
Perhaps the only tip is to the floor, when the walnut wood appears to us as too delicate to the house with the dog.
Word of architects, Ing. arch. Lenka Langerov<0xC3><0xA1> and MgA. Kamila Hornychov<0xC3><0xA1>, author of the realization.
The apartment is on the last floor of the new building, therefore it was possible to make a completely new layout solution and several other modifications within the construction.
For the interior, an important element is the placement of light conduits in the ceiling of the hallway and the main toilet.
This brought daylight to the darker areas of the apartment.
Also, the direct entrance from the main bathroom to the roof terrace to the pool from USSPA is one of the construction modifications that was very beneficial for the function of the whole apartment.
There is also a swimming pool and a hot tub.
Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim living in Prague.
You're from France.
Where did you live before you moved to New York?
My parents are of Algerian descent.
I was born in the south of France, just off the Spanish border.
I've moved quite a bit.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
In France, I studied journalism, so I got to work in a magazine.
So why did you decide to move out of the country?
I started to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere between people.
I think that every Frenchman is very negative.
People in France are in a negative mood in general, but lately it has worsened even more.
It is interesting that you mention the negativity.
This is how some people evaluate the Czech nature.
Believe me, you're not negative compared to the French.
Some people may not get it when they come to France because they don’t see it as much as tourists.
But it was too much for me.
The big issue is money.
People feel that they have little money, while the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which is enough in my opinion.
Now there is a problem with the behavior of people towards Muslims.
That's totally incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street where I lived, my non-Muslim neighbor started looking at me through his fingers just because I was a Muslim.
It's like I'm some kind of evil.
That's why I didn't feel good in France.
But my family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job virtually anywhere else and I came across a vacancy with Air France here in Prague.
I admit that I did not know Prague at all from the beginning.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I did not know what to expect from Prague.
I've been here for three years now, and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Mainly because of a completely different atmosphere.
Maybe it's because I don't speak Czech, so I can't catch any negative reactions or insults, but I feel like people are freer here.
That I can do anything, dress anyway, and no one's gonna judge me.
In France, someone is always looking at you inconveniently, even if you have special clothes and the like.
I started to feel really free in Prague.
I don't think smokers care about that sort of thing.
Where do you work now?
After working at Air France, I worked for a travel website for a while.
Then a friend and I set up a website where people offer and look for shared housing.
So far we only operate in Prague, but we would like to extend this to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends here, who are half Czechs, and two other Czech friends.
I have to say that another specificity of the Czechs is that at first they keep more distance.
He won't let anyone get so close to his body.
That’s a big difference from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses on their face.
It's different here, but I understand it's a cultural issue, so I'm trying to adapt.
You mentioned that you don't speak Czech.
Is the language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, I have it quite simple in Prague, because maybe everyone here speaks English.
Even at dinners or in food.
I'd like to learn Czech, but I don't have that much time.
And because everyone can communicate a little bit in English, I don’t have that need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there's someone to help me.
Have you had any negative reactions as well?
Is it because you are a Muslim?
Well, not really.
Perhaps this is also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My manager, the Czech Republic, once told me about the French football team and said something in the sense: After all, they are not French, but Africans.
It really touched me a lot.
But if anyone has a problem with being a Muslim, that hasn’t happened to me yet.
And this despite the fact that a colleague once pointed me to some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He told me not to go to the center, that they would insult me there.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly related to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something like this could happen in Paris, Nice or Brussels?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is that anything can happen anywhere nowadays.
Until recently, I could not have imagined that something like this would happen in France.
This is not just about Muslims.
Islam does not recognize violence at all.
For me, the people who kill are not Muslims.
The Quran says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel when terrorists protect themselves with your faith?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, even if I shouldn’t feel that way.
I try not to follow the reports of violence very much, but every time I read something, I have a need to apologize for something that is not really my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for the terrorists?
We met at Ji<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xAD>ho z Pod<0xC4><0x9B>brad Square.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims and Christians protested against the violence.
Did you register it?
I didn't know that.
But I understand that these people feel the need to prove that they don't agree with violence.
I don't think they'd have to do anything like that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn’t do?
Do you meet with other Muslims in Prague?
My co-workers, for example, are from Egypt and other Muslim countries.
They’re a little more religiously grounded than I am, so we sometimes have a pretty wild discussion of Islam because we all perceive it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, maybe they were studying Islam in school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordinate status of a woman.
How do you feel about that?
I am not submissive in any way.
Quite the opposite.
I am a woman, I have strength.
It’s also because you don’t wear a head covering.
A hijab, for example?
And it's mainly about the way I've been raised.
My mother, for example, is a fundamental Muslim.
He prays five times a day, but does not wear a scarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It all depends on how you interpret it.
When one reads the Qur'an, one should make one's own opinion of these things.
So when I read a passage in the Qur’an that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself: I am not the Prophet’s wife, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect that, and when I come to Iran or Saudi Arabia, where the scarves are required, I will take it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
So far, yes.
Nowhere else did I feel so good.
I’ve been thinking about Poland for a while, but I’m doing great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
Prague is the ideal city for this.
