The TV director Mat<0xC4><0x9B>j Li<0xC5><0xA1>ka and the manager of the Prague music club Marek Greger are behind the idea to use the already planned routes for transporting shipments.
With the idea, they brought three applications with different geographical reach to life.
We launched the national transfer application in May.
At the moment, there are thousands of cities uploaded in it and we will expand the network.
In the Czech Republic, we first want to learn this before we focus more on abroad, says a forty-year-old manager in an interview for iDNES.cz.
How does the Transfer app work and who can benefit from it?
You download it and register for free.
Then you can enter the route and the data, how big the package you can transfer and how much you want for it.
Someone might ask for a ride that day.
When the route and the delivery time match, it pairs and both come with a mutual notification.
At that moment, the chat will open, where the couple will arrange a transfer.
How many people do you think would have to register in order for each package to always find its courier?
I don’t know the ideal state, I can’t estimate how many registered and how many trips it takes to make the coverage completely optimal and each offer matched the demand.
It is already working on the main tracks and it is logically easier than on the road between the villages.
The more people, the greater the potential for speed and accuracy.
People are also building trust so far and finding that no one escapes with the package.
Haven't you had to deal with a case like this yet?
How many users does the service have after two months of launch?
Right now, we have about 5,000 to 6,000 people creating roads.
We see this as a success and we believe that there will be more to come.
Isn't there a risk that the sender will wait too long?
We hope that we will be a competition for large conglomerates only because we are able to deliver the item, for example, on the same day and for a fraction of the price.
For a large company, you will pay several thousand for delivery within two hours.
You'll pay a hundred less here, because that's the path someone's already taking.
Should traditional carriers be afraid of a possible loss of customers in the future?
We hope that's the way it is.
The market has huge potential, it feeds huge multinational carriers, as well as business chains where everyone started shopping and gradually found that quality does not match what it pays for.
No one wants to find a note in their mailbox that says they have to pick up the shipment at the branch office, not earlier than the day after 7 p.m.
At the time, I needed the package for six hours and I waited at home because it was important.
We want a better, faster and more functional service that doesn’t bother anyone and sends a signal to the competition that they should try.
