Military Officers Distorted ISIS Intelligence, Says Parliamentary Committee
The parliamentary committee said in a report released Thursday that officers from the U.S. Central Command had altered intelligence reports to portray a more optimistic picture of the war against Islamic State in Iraq and Syria than the events from the country provided.
According to a preliminary report by the Republican Chairman of the Armed Forces Committee, the Intelligence Committee, and the Subcommittee on Defense, a “large dissatisfaction” among central intelligence analysts was found, according to which their superiors altered their assessment of the U.S. effort.
The Central Headquarters, known as CentCom, is the military headquarters in Tampa, Florida, overseeing U.S. military operations in the Middle East and Central Asia.
The press release to the report reads: “The intelligence reports approved by senior Centcom officers usually offered a more positive picture of U.S. counter-terrorism efforts than were confirmed by facts on the ground, and were consistently more positive than the analyses obtained from other sources.”
“What happened at Centcom is unacceptable — our fighters are hurt when misanalysis is presented to senior policymakers,” said Ken Calvert, a congressman and Republican from California.
The failure of Centcom's leadership reaches to the top of the organization.
The ten-page report describes in detail the persistent problems of the Central Staff in describing and analysing U.S. efforts in training Iraqi forces in 2014 and 2015.
While there is no conclusive evidence that the Obama administration’s top officials ordered the reports to be amended, the report says analysts had the impression that they were under pressure from Centcom leaders to present a more optimistic view of the dangers posed by Islamic State.
“In the first half of 2015, many of the Central Staff’s press releases, statements and congressional statements were significantly more positive than what the events actually were,” the report said.
For example, a Centcom official publicly stated that a major military attack to take over Mosul could begin as early as April or May 2015.
Mosul, Iraq’s second-largest city, remains under Islamic State control.
"This is clear after months of investigation," said Mike Pompeo, a Republican representative from Kansas.
From mid-2014 to mid-2015, top-ranking U.S. Central Intelligence Agency staff manipulated the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency’s outputs in order to downplay the dangers of ISIS in Iraq.
The Republicans set up a task force after they learned of analysts' concerns that intelligence services' information about the Islamic State were being manipulated.
After the report published on Thursday, further investigations must follow.
Centcom’s intelligence services are still under investigation by the Inspector General of the Ministry of Defence.
Democratic members of the Committee on Intelligence released their own findings on Thursday, which matched some of the findings of the Republican working group.
“Between 2014 and 2015, Centcom created a very narrow process for compiling assessments of information about ISIS and Iraqi security forces,” said Adam B. Schiff, chairman of the committee and a representative of the Democrats.
According to Adam Schiff, this process "led to distort intelligence outputs," damaged morale among analysts, and "insufficiently taken into account dissenting views."
However, Schiff and the Democrats say they have found no evidence that the White House is trying to pressure Centcom analysts to adjust their findings based on “the premise or the political situation.”
The preliminary results of the parliamentary inquiry were published in the Daily Beast on Tuesday.
Last August, the New York Times reported on an ongoing investigation by the Pentagon inspector general, which was launched following complaints from Centcom analysts.
Lieutenant Commander Patrick Evans, a Pentagon spokesman, said in a statement that the Defense Ministry would not comment on the parliamentary report as the Inspector General’s investigation was still ongoing.
But he said that “experts sometimes disagree on the interpretation of complex data, and that the intelligence community and the Ministry of Defense welcome a healthy dialogue on these crucial issues of national security.”
The investigation has implications beyond the question of whether the American-led bombing in Iraq and Syria is successful (a verdict that now declares a growing number of defense officials).
However, last year’s indictment raised questions about the extent to which President Obama can rely on the central staff to honestly assess military operations in Iraq, Afghanistan, Libya and other crisis locations.
