“Protestant Generations” in Ethiopia, a longtime US ally
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Demonstrators demanding political change in Ethiopia have met with violent opposition from the government.
Witnesses say many protesters were shot dead during clashes with police.
Is there a threat of war in Ethiopia?
Over the past decade, it has been one of the most stable nations in Africa, a strong Western alliance with a fast-growing economy.
In recent months, however, the country has been gripped by anti-government unrest, which has spread to more and more areas.
Thousands of people have taken to the streets in the last week alone, demanding fundamental political change.
According to human rights organizations, the government’s response was relentless.
Witnesses say police officers shot and killed crowds of unarmed demonstrators.
Video footage of the protests, likely from late last year or early this year, captures security forces beating young people with sticks after being forced to stand by the wall on their hands.
The UN High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
“It has always been difficult to keep this country together and to take a step forward will be even harder,” said Rashid Abdi, head of the Horn of Africa project for the International Crisis Group.
After Nigeria, Ethiopia is the second most populous nation in Africa and its stability is supported by the West.
U.S. military and intelligence services are working closely with Ethiopians to eliminate the dangers of a terrorist attack in the area, especially in Somalia, and few of the African countries, if any, are getting such assistance from the West.
The economy of Ethiopia has developed at an impressive pace.
Its infrastructure has improved significantly - there is even a new suburban train in the capital Addis Ababa.
And the streets of the city are typically quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia can hardly be described as a model of democracy - an organization that fights for human rights without ceasing to talk about government repression - the opposition in the country has been suppressed, dissidents effectively silenced.
Many of them have been expelled, imprisoned, killed, or driven far into the desert.
But that can change.
“When you strangle people and they have no choice but to protest, there will be a breakthrough,” said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer at a university in central Ethiopia.
All the youth are protesting.
It has been protesting for a generation.
There are many complaints and they concern everything from land disputes to absolute control of the ruling coalition.
After last year’s widely criticized elections, the ruling party and its allies have won the last chair held by the opposition and now control 100 percent in parliament.
At the same time, the pressure on the border with Eritrea is increasing, and the conflict along this inaccurate, controversial border has claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Anylitists fear that separatist groups that have been more or less suppressed over the past few years, such as the Orom Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the confusion and re-arm themselves.
There are several factors that explain why now, after years of simmering beneath the surface, these bitter feelings have rekindled.
The first one is seemingly harmless: smart phones.
Many Ethiopians can communicate through social networks only in the last few years, when cheaper smartphones have become commonly available and Internet services have improved.
And even if the government bans access to Facebook or Twitter, as is usually the case during protests, many people can still communicate through Internet proxies that hide the location of these people.
Several young Ethiopians spoke about how they gathered at the protests.
There is also greater solidarity between the Oroms and the Amharas, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
Orom and Amhar are not natural allies.
For centuries, the Amhars, mostly from the Christian highlands of Ethiopia, excelled in politics and commerce, and used the Oroms, many of whom are Muslim and live in lowlands.
But that's also changing.
"We are on our way to a unified leadership," said Mulatu Gemechu, the leader of Orom.
The largest protests took place in the areas inhabited by Amhara and Oroma.
Many Amhars and Oroms believe that Ethiopia is wrongly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnic group, which makes up about 6 percent of the population and controls the army, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third cause of the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Zenawi, a former rebel leader, served as Ethiopian Prime Minister for 17 years until his death in 2012, when he succumbed to an unspecified disease.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could see around the corner.
Analysts say he was particularly masterful in detecting initial signals of dissatisfaction and used ambassadors to process and win over opponents.
“The current regime lacks basic knowledge,” said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalegn, was pulled out of relative ignorance in order to replace Zenawi.
Unlike Zenawi, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say they have no confidence in security services controlled by the Tigers.
Many fear that the result will be further bloodshed.
Ethiopia last experienced such turmoil in 2005 after thousands of people protested against what analysts called an election that the government robbed and then stole.
It was followed by a hard hit, during which many protesters were killed - albeit less than in recent months - and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia’s leaders for visionary infrastructure planning, such as a new suburban train and measurable progress in the fight against poverty.
However, it is quite clear that the gradual increase in disputes within the Ethiopian government has not stopped it.
And there is a dangerous ethnic formation taking place.
Last month, protesters in the Amharic city of Gondar attacked Tigris-owned businesses, and resentment against the Tigris on social media is becoming more and more common.
Analysts say the protests put the U.S. and other Western allies at odds.
The U.S. government is using Ethiopia as a base for drone overflights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently said the base was closed.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, at the same time it does not want its allies to break up in an already volatile region.
"That," said Abdi, "is a very sharp edge of the blade."
