Kepler measures the rotation speed of stars in the Pleiades
The Kepler Space Telescope's latest mission to assist astronomers is to obtain an almost complete list of the rotational speeds of stars from the Pleiades cluster.
The new data helps astronomers understand why the stars in the cluster rotate at different speeds, and also how the rotation time is related to the formation of the planet.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will learn more about the relationship between stellar matter, its age and even history in its solar system," Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Infrared Pasade Processing and Analysis Center, said in a new report.
The Pleiades star cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster are now reaching adulthood and formed over 125 million years ago.
Now it spins the fastest.
At the moments of maximum rotational speeds, these teenage stars release huge amounts of stellar wind.
Because these winds move along the magnetic fields of stars, they have a slowing effect on them.
As a star ages, its rotational speed also slows down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by measuring the time between the discovery of discernible points on stars -- similar to sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotational speeds, larger stars rotate slower than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to the dancers, the bigger ones make the pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades, we see that slower rotating stars are more massive, while those that spin the fastest are usually very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the quality of stars and the speed of rotation.
"The Pleiades provide us with an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, in younger and older stars," Rebull said.
There’s still a lot we want to learn about how, when, and why stars slow down their spinning speed and so to say “hang their dancing shoes on a nail.”
Rebull and her colleagues described in detail the latest analysis of the rotational speeds of the Pleiades in three studies, which will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a Qualification Agreement Necessary?
If I did not sign up, would the qualification agreement not be concluded and after a few months I could move to another hospital?
Is it even possible to work after graduation without enrolling in a specialization education?
My point is that in the field where I would like to work, there is now a job vacancy only in a slightly more distant hospital, but in about half a year there could be a job vacancy in another one, where I would like to work afterwards.
So I don’t know how to deal with the situation about that half-year, the question continues.
Replies to Mgr. Lenka Wolfov<0xC3><0xA1>.
No legislation provides for an obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with an employer - a hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institution regulated by the Labour Code and may be concluded between the employee and the employer in order to ensure the reimbursement of the costs incurred in increasing or deepening the employee’s qualifications.
In the field of health, however, there is long-term pressure to not conclude these agreements with a view to ensuring the labour mobility of healthcare workers and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
According to Law No. 95/2004 Coll., on the conditions for obtaining and recognising professional qualifications and specialised qualifications for the exercise of the medical profession of a doctor, a dentist and a pharmacist, it is expressly stated that participation in specialised training is considered to enhance the qualification (not to increase it).
This means that a qualification agreement can be concluded according to the Labour Code only if the costs reach at least CZK 75,000.
There is no legal obligation to enroll in specialised education.
The law only lays down the conditions for applying for inclusion in the field of specialised education.
However, according to the law, the doctor is authorized to perform the profession of a doctor already due to the completion of the necessary university studies, although under the conditions stipulated by the law (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The law provides for a situation in which professional practice completed in another field of specialization can be included in the specialization education of a doctor, if its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
Theoretically, it would be possible to calculate the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the situation of the interviewer.
However, given the fact that I do not know the circumstances of this case, it is advisable to consult the relevant committee of the Ministry of Health (Committee of Science and Medical Professions), since the Ministry of Health by law provides an advisory and advisory service related to the inclusion in the course of specialization education and its course.
The Czech Medical Chamber also provides the advisory service free of charge, of which every doctor must be a member.
